CampusCare Prototype Statement: Testing.

To test the functionality of the CampusCare prototype on the user profile of all user groups, i.e., students, doctors, and administrators, our team undertook two usability tests on the prototype. This was aimed at making sure that all of the features were functional and that the experience was easy and user friendly. We also did the testing using real users who typify each group and the users were requested to perform specific tasks including registering, logging in, making reservations, checking schedules, and maintaining their profiles. During the initial testing phase, we have also found out that there were a number of issues that would not allow users to accomplish their work without complications. Students have claimed that the first button to be clicked on was the login and that was not responsive thus confusing them and leaving them with frustration. Mismatched passwords at registration did not give any error message, hence, the user could continue without awareness of the fact that there was a mistake made. Also, upon making an appointment, a confirmation screen was not present and thus the students were not sure whether or not their appointment had been made. The doctors had complained that the schedule view in the mobile devices was not working properly, with the display being cut off, and the name of the patients being cut short and they were unable to read essential information. Administrators were also met with some decisive issues in which addition and modification of doctor information were not saved and the analytics charts were empty without any data visible. The log out button was difficult to locate across all users as it was located in the bottom of the screen, and response time between screens was really slow. Overall, we found fourteen issues, of which five were critical problems that prevented the basic functionality and four high-priority issues that had a considerable influence on the user experience. Round 1 only had a completion rate of sixty eight percent and user satisfaction at a low three point two out of five.

We had an emergency sprint review and retrospective after evaluating all the feedback to rank fixes and set them as the priority of team members. We firstly set to work at getting the acute problems solved. In the case of the non-reactive login button, we have placed a loading state indicator and corrected the click event handler such that the button now reacts immediately with visual response. We have also applied real-time validation on the password confirmation field, a red error message with a clear text of Passwords do not match, this way the user cannot enter the site before correcting the error. Booking was also accompanied by a confirmation screen showing all the information about the appointment and an option of adding it to the calendar and students now have a definite feeling that their booking was successful. In the case of doctors, we entirely reformatted the schedule view on mobile in the form of a scrollable horizontal table, such that it is fully visible on all gadgets without any information being lost. Fields containing patient names were extended to include hover tooltips making it possible to always read a full name. On our part, administrators, we corrected the database connection in the prototype and put a saved successfully message, hence the profile updates are now stored and users get the immediate feedback. The analytics graphs were also linked to sample data where loading indicators have been added hence, charts have meaningful information. We scaled images and minimized effects on the animations, thus, making screen changes forty percent faster. We also included Back and Cancel buttons along the booking flow in order to allow the user to move easily without having to start anew. The log out button was placed on the upper right hand side as is the norm and thus, the user finds it instantly. We also tried to standardize colors of the buttons throughout the application with the primary being green and secondary being gray, minimum font size was raised to sixteen pixels to make it easier to read, and all form fields had a placeholder text to explain what input was required. All of the issues that were determined during Round 1 were methodically discussed and resolved.

After all fixes we ran Round 2 testing with the same users to test our fixes. The findings revealed tremendous improvement in all measures. The login button was instant and there was no need to make any error prior to verification of the passwords and each booking was completed with a definite confirmation screen. Physicians would be able to see their entire schedules on their phones without any reduction and truncation. Administrators were able to add and edit physician profiles with change saved correctly, and the analytics graphs were able to display appropriate data as well. The completion rate of the tasks increased to ninety six percent compared to sixty eight percent which implied that users were now able to perform almost all tasks without the help provided. The level of user satisfaction increased by three point two to four point seven out of five with students, doctors and administrators themselves showing true enthusiasm regarding the ease with which the system was now. The responsiveness of the logins and the new confirmation screen, which has left no confusion as to the presence of an appointment were particularly commended by students. Physicians liked the more convenient mobile vision that enabled them to examine schedules simultaneously without hassles in zooming and scrolling. The fact that profile updates could now be saved reliably and the analytics graphs could give meaningful insights on just a glance made administrators especially delighted. We have resolved all the five critical issues and tolerated only one minor issue, which we have considered to be improved in the future. The time to perform activities was also reduced by half, as it was close to five minutes before and now it is a little bit more than two minutes, which is to say that the system was not only more reliable, but also much more efficient. All three profile tests showed that CampusCare is now fully functional and operational with all types of users finding it easy to register and make appointments, doctors can view and manage their schedules without any technical difficulties, and administrators are capable of managing profile management and analytics without any technical problems. This experience of defining issues to providing solutions and testing their effectiveness taught us the huge importance of the iterative process of testing and user feedbacks. We also got to know that designers tend to become too attached to their work and they fail to see problems that a real user picks up quickly. We have found that mobile testing cannot be a follow-up since desktop functionality does not ensure mobile usability. We realized that effective error messages and confirmation screens do not only help to provide such a nice addition but also create user trust and confidence. 
